I do believe that you&#39;ve found a bug in how the scheduler works.  It purports to accept a `TimeUnit`, but if you look at the `ScheduledAnnotationBeanPostProcessor`, you&#39;ll see these lines:

    long fixedDelay = convertToMillis(scheduled.fixedDelay(), scheduled.timeUnit());
	if (fixedDelay &gt;= 0) {
        Assert.isTrue(!processedSchedule, errorMessage);
        ...
    }

The first part of this converts your microseconds to milliseconds.  That logic simply does a division, `duration / milliRatio`.  Your duration is set to `1` per the fixedDelay property, the ratio of milliseconds to microseconds is 1000, so this returns 1/1000, which rounds up to 0.  This will drop you into the `if` block and since this process has yet to be scheduled, fails the assertion and throws the caught exception.

In other words, it looks like if you pass in microseconds or nanoseconds as a time unit, it&#39;s not going to work.

You might think that you can set this to something that will equate to a positive value, but then you&#39;ll find another trap a few lines lower when it checks the fixed rate.

